## DBCCSS('A-REI.4.b')
## DBsubject('Algebra')
## DBchapter('Basic Algebra')
## DBsection('equations', 'Simplification')
## KEYWORDS('rational','domain')
## Author('Alex Jordan, Carl Yao, Chris Hughes')
## Institution('PCC')

##############################################
DOCUMENT();        # This should be the first executable line in the problem.

loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "PGML.pl",
  "PCCmacros.pl",
  "extraAnswerEvaluators.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl"
);

##############################################

TEXT(beginproblem());
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$a =  non_zero_random(-10,10,1);
$b = random(2,5,1);

do {$f = RandomVariableName();} until ($f ne 'x');

Context("Interval");
$ans = Interval("(-infinity,0)U(0,infinity)");

##############################################

BEGIN_PGML

Using interval notation, the domain of the function [`[$f]`] defined by    
    [``[$f](x)=\frac{x+[$a]}{x^{[$b]}}``] is [__________________________________]{$ans}

If the answer includes more than one interval write the intervals separated by the union symbol, *U*. If the answer uses [`-\infty`], input *-inf*; if the answer uses [`\infty`], input *inf*. 
END_PGML

##############################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

The only potential for an invalid input value would be if the denominator of this expression works out to [`0`]. Since the only number making the denominator [`0`] is [`x=0`], the domain is [`[$ans]`].

END_PGML_SOLUTION


ENDDOCUMENT();        # This should be the last executable line in the problem.
